Gall (
Figs 52–55
). The galls are integral to leaf blades of young leaves with swelling on both sides of the leaf, brownish, 3-4 mm in diameter and extending up to 2.7 mm from the leaf surface (n = 10 ). Galls grow individually on a leaf rather than aggregated together. Gall tissue is succulent when young and the gall becomes hollow once the larva matures and pupates inside. The pupa can roll freely inside the gall.
